[tikz]
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
\draw[->] (0,0)--(0,8.4);
\draw[->] (0,0)--(5.5,0);
\foreach \v/\p in {5000/0,5100/1,5200/2,5300/3,5400/4,5500/5,5600/6,5700/7} {\draw (-0.2,\p)--(0,\p); \node[left,font=\scriptsize] at (-0.2,\p) {$\v$};}
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (0.6,0) rectangle (1.6,2.8);
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (2.0,0) rectangle (3.0,6.8);
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (3.4,0) rectangle (4.4,0.8);
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (1.1,0) {Ashby};
\node[below,font=\tiny] at (2.5,0) {Belford};
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (3.9,0) {Corby};
\node[rotate=90,font=\small] at (-1.9,3.5) {Population};
\node[below,font=\small] at (2.50,-1.0) {Town};
\node[font=\small] at (2.5,8.1) {Town populations};
\end{tikzpicture}
[/tikz]
Why does this graph make Belford's population look far greater than Ashby's?

[tikz]
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
\draw[->] (0,0)--(0,7.4);
\draw[->] (0,0)--(4.8,0);
\foreach \v/\p in {100/1,200/2,300/3,400/4,500/5,600/6} {\draw (-0.2,\p)--(0,\p); \node[left,font=\scriptsize] at (-0.2,\p) {$\v$};}
\node[left,font=\small] at (-0.2,0) {$0$};
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (0.6,0) rectangle (1.2,5);
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (2.0,0) rectangle (3.6,5.5);
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (0.9,0) {Shop A};
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (2.8,0) {Shop B};
\node[rotate=90,font=\small] at (-1.3,3) {Sales (units)};
\node[below,font=\small] at (1.85,-1.0) {Shop};
\node[font=\small] at (2.2,7.1) {Monthly sales by shop};
\end{tikzpicture}
[/tikz]
Shop A sold $500$ items and Shop B sold $550$. What makes this graph misleading?

[tikz]
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
\fill[orange!40,draw=black] (0,0) rectangle (0.8,0.8);
\fill[orange!40,draw=black] (2.2,0) rectangle (3.8,1.6);
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (0.4,0) {2020};
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (3.0,0) {2021};
\node[above,font=\small] at (0.4,0.8) {$100$};
\node[above,font=\small] at (3.0,1.6) {$200$};
\node[font=\scriptsize] at (1.7,2.6) {Students achieving Band 6};
\end{tikzpicture}
[/tikz]
The number of students achieving Band 6 doubled from $100$ to $200$. Why does the pictograph overstate the increase?

[tikz]
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
\draw[->] (0,0)--(0,4.4);
\draw[->] (0,0)--(5.2,0);
\foreach \v/\p in {10/1,20/2,30/3} {\draw (-0.2,\p)--(0,\p); \node[left,font=\scriptsize] at (-0.2,\p) {$\v$};}
\node[left,font=\small] at (-0.2,0) {$0$};
\foreach \x/\lbl in {1/2014,2.5/2015,4/2019} {\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (\x,0) {\lbl};}
\draw[thick,blue] (1,1)--(2.5,2)--(4,3);
\fill[blue] (1,1) circle (2pt) (2.5,2) circle (2pt) (4,3) circle (2pt);
\node[rotate=90,font=\small] at (-0.9,1.5) {Sales (1000s)};
\node[below,font=\small] at (2.50,-1.0) {Year};
\node[font=\small] at (2.5,4.1) {Yearly sales};
\end{tikzpicture}
[/tikz]
Why does this line graph make the sales look like they rose at a steady rate?

[tikz]
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
\draw[->] (0,0)--(0,4.4);
\draw[->] (0,0)--(5.2,0);
\foreach \v/\p in {20/1,40/2,60/3} {\draw (-0.2,\p)--(0,\p); \node[left,font=\scriptsize] at (-0.2,\p) {$\v\%$};}
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (0.6,0) rectangle (1.6,3.0);
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (2.0,0) rectangle (3.0,2.75);
\fill[blue!25,draw=black] (3.4,0) rectangle (4.4,2.25);
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (1.1,0) {Maths};
\node[below,font=\tiny] at (2.5,0) {English};
\node[below,font=\tiny] at (3.9,0) {Science};
\node[rotate=90,font=\small] at (-2.0,1.5) {Share of A grades};
\node[below,font=\scriptsize] at (2.50,-1.0) {Subject};
\node[font=\scriptsize] at (2.5,4.1) {Share of the school's A grades};
\end{tikzpicture}
[/tikz]
The graph claims to show each subject's share of the school's A grades ($60\%$, $55\%$, $45\%$). Why is it misleading?

